My wife is a data engineer and has been wanting me to learn a little bit about what she does, so I tried a couple of different options. This so far has been the best one. The information is concise and there is practice throughout each lesson. There‚Äôs more than one way to get to answer, however she did say that as I progress these little differences will cause problems. Either way, I‚Äôve been having a lot of fun learning what she does.

Additionally, I learn by having a lot of practice to implement what I‚Äôve learned. I subscribed to the pro version because I was under the impression that I would have unlimited practice. content:
SoloLearn is really good- you get tons of coding courses for free. I‚Äôve been using it for about two years now and it has rarely failed me. I recommend it first to anyone who asks me where they should learn to code. 

The Q&A is well-moderated and the courses are in good detail for the most part. The playground is a great place to test your code. All in all, Sololearn is a great tool if you want to test something really quick, or refer to a course if you are looking for quick information. This is especially useful when you have the app.

However, there are one or two problems I might report here in order that it gets fixed. In the mobile app, when you have the keyboard down in a code and click the < arrow button, it sees I havent saved the code and asks me to name it and save it. This is really useful, because without it I would have had too many projects lost because I never saved. However, it never prompts you if you have the keyboard up. For example, I was working on a project for over an hour on my mobile, and was expecting it to ask me to save when I pressed the < button (I had the keyboard up) and it never prompts me to save so all my progress was gone, which I was not expecting to happen. 

Also, some courses aren‚Äôt complete. The PHP course is missing a lot of important shadings revolving around opening and closing files.

I had spent long hard hours staring at a simple python program wondering why it wouldn‚Äôt work. It was a simple program: you input into one file, and the program puts the result in the output file. What would be an easy file error fix took me hours to troubleshoot (who knew that file.read() closes the file, resulting in errors if you want to read the file line by line?). Just these small tidbits of advice in the courses can save programmers lots of time.
title: Its great, some problems though

review: The app has lots of great content, a great interface, and you can learn whatever you want and at your own pace. The main problem with the app is the constant prompting to check out new features, invite friends, and overall spend more time on the app. Thank you very much, but I downloaded your app to learn one thing, (python) and I do not want to start on another programming language before I get the basics of the first one. The individual python app was much better, simpler, and had less distractions. Too bad the developers have been limiting that app. Edit: Clearly the developers of the app are not taking reviews seriously. My review of the app says that the app is very informative, and has great content, however the individual Python app was far superior. No, I do not need to be told that the individual app is going to be discontinued, I already understood that from previous reviews, and many prompts from within the app itself.
replyContent:
Hi,

Please be informed that separate apps are going to be discontinued soon. That is why we recommend to switch to all-in one-version, which has better user experience.
For more information, please contact us via info@sololearn.com and we will help.

through Java, python, and html on here. Each course is broken into bite 
sized sections with quizzes and a easy to access module that let's you 
write your own code or try stuff that's being talked about in the lesson.

into a topic you don't understand someone in the comments so be there front 
and center explaining in detail how it works! This might be 4 stars without 
comments in, but as it stands it's worth all 5!
